						<img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/footballbyfootball-dev/lockerroom/lock-mattflag.jpg" alt="" style="float: left; padding: 20px; padding-left: 0;">

						<p>The idea that someone in the NFL thought emphasizing “illegal contact” was a good idea is hard to swallow if you love football.  Not grabbing or holding, mind you.  Touching. 
						 
						<p>Touching. 
						 
						<p>Imagine armor-clad knights getting all dressed up only to be punished for touching one another.  It’s completely asinine. 
						 
						<p>That said, unfortunately you have to deal with stupid in today’s NFL.  So how does a linebacker, who lives his professional life at the edge of the illegal contact zone 5 yards from the line of scrimmage, still do his job? 
						 
						<p>Under these circumstances, your best chance is to first count away from the line of scrimmage before the snap to get a sense of where you’re standing...at 3, 4, or 5 yards, etc.  From there, once the play has started, remember about where you began and hope the action doesn’t cause you to lose that exact reference point.  In other words, yeah right.     
						 
						<p>An off-the-ball linebacker is generally covering someone from the box (a tight end or back) that he has to absorb and cover as they run their route.  Sometimes the linebacker is aligned over a wide receiver to disrupt his release and then drop into a zone.  It should go without saying, but all the dudes a linebacker has to cover are fast as hell and/or exceptionally quick. 
						 
						<p>Imagine the player the linebacker is covering goes in motion.  Or he runs his route crossing another eligible receiver’s path, and in the chase the linebacker’s responsibility switches to another player. Or as he steps up to meet a running back in the hole, the back fakes protection and then releases into the pattern.   
						 
						<p>Suffice it say, you don’t turn and start counting white lines.  A rule that requires you to do so without committing a game infraction is clearly idiotic.  At best, it’s a guessing game in real time for players.  Always has been, always will be. 
						 
						<p>The players are there to compete against one another.  Not against a poorly written and conceived rule infatuation. 
						 
						<p>As a player, you just do your best and hope you get lucky until the officials remember strict interpretations of the rules are hopelessly unrealistic.  It’s an exercise for everyone involved in playing pretend. 
						 
						<p>The NFL season will go on.  Hopefully for football players and fans, the ‘emphasis’ on illegal contact won’t.
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

