				<div class="lockerrooom-entry-content cf">
					<p>Just another Emphasis Scare

					<p>The new ‘point of emphasis’ on illegal downfield contact heading into the 2014 season is the same speech that NFL officials and the NFL competition committee have been spitting out for over a decade.  For 8 years (2001-2008 seasons) I sat in an NFL officials meeting during training camp and listened to ‘points of emphasis’ for the upcoming season.  At least 5 of those years we, as receivers and defensive backs collectively, were told that downfield contact and holding was going to be a focus point and scrutinized more tightly.  It never changed long term, and this year will follow the same pattern.  

					<p>To be clear, this isn’t to say that the game hasn’t been slanted in favor of offense.  Offense, as the NFL sees it, puts people in the seats and advertisers on an easy sell.  This transformation happened years ago and is the subject of a separate debate.

					<p>Here’s the life-cycle of the new point of emphasis.  To start, there will be more flags.  Referees will be on heightened alert for all contact downfield and will want to prove that they are respecting the “new” rule, the NFL competition committee and the NFL executive office.  But players have trained years—some decades—at footwork, handwork and strategy.  Those techniques are now instinct.  Although for the last month they’ve been told they can’t do something in practice, or have been flagged for something in a preseason game, that doesn't mean they won’t revert back to what has been ingrained.  

					<p>When their livelihood depends on their performance over a 2 second time frame, a new rule that has been deemed an ‘emphasis point’ isn’t going to matter.  

					<p>With this said, referees don’t want to determine the course of real games or be the focal point.  Coaches, players, and most importantly fans, get extremely irritated when they feel that players aren’t allowed to play freely…or take a back seat to referees. This will quickly bring the downfield level of contact and hand use back to what it has been for the last 8-10 years.

					<p>This latest round of emphasis talk is just another waste of time.
				</div>
