					<div class="lockerrooom-entry-content cf">
						<p>The much criticized illegal contact rule and its “point of emphasis” will have an impact for the quarterbacks this year.  If it continues to be called as it has been in the preseason, there will be certain teaching points that the older quarterbacks may use to help their team.
						 
						<p>Let me state something that most people already know, the veteran quarterbacks are an extended arm of the coaching staff and a direct link to the players.  Coaching points that come from a quarterback to a player often times have much more impact than that from the coaches themselves.  So throughout the week, the solidified veteran quarterbacks will have some of their own meetings and discuss routes and coverages with their wide receivers.  During this time, many other things are discussed, such as game situations and what the quarterback may be thinking.
						 
						<p>This is where I feel this “point of emphasis” may be used.  In the past, receivers have been coached to use leverage and other techniques to gain separation from the defender.  The simplified rule is that if a defender is there first, he has the right to his ground.  There were instances in the preseason of receivers or tight ends running right into the defensive player who was there first, earning a flag for illegal contact. 
						 
						<p>I think that quarterbacks may use that to their advantage, and rather than avoiding contact, embrace it.  Encourage contact to their receivers, and hope for the call—especially on 3rd & long. 
						 
						<p>Because even if it’s 3rd and forever, a five yard illegal contact penalty means an automatic first down.  Advantage:  offense. 
